of mirtazapine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Alpha-2 adrenergic receptor blockade","Selective serotonin reuptake inhibition","Noradrenaline reuptake inhibition","Dopamine reuptake inhibition","Monoamine oxidase inhibition"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe principal mechanism of mirtazapine is \u003Cstrong\u003Ealpha-2 adrenergic receptor blockade\u003C/strong\u003E. This enhances both noradrenaline and serotonin release in synapses. Additionally, mirtazapine antagonises histamine H1 receptors, which explains its sedating effects and tendency to increase appetite.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelective serotonin reuptake inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of drugs like fluoxetine and sertraline\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoradrenaline reuptake inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E is seen with drugs like reboxetine\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDopamine reuptake inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary mechanism of bupropion\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonoamine oxidase inhibition\u003C/strong\u003E describes older antidepressants like phenelzine\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMirtazapine\u0027s unique combination of receptor effects makes it particularly useful in depression with sleep disturbance and weight loss.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mirtazapine blocks alpha-2 adrenergic receptors, enhancing both noradrenaline and serotonin neurotransmission.","Histamine H1 receptor antagonism by mirtazapine leads to sedation and increased appetite, making it useful for depression with sleep and appetite disturbances.","Mirtazapine\u0027s unique mechanism differs from other antidepressants that work through reuptake inhibition or enzyme blockade."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50628"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14680"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50628"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-25T20:10:39+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-25T20:11:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7373"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65191"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co